  "notes": [
    "The Environmental Science major is an immersive, multifaceted experience. It emphasizes real-world practice-- getting students off campus to solve problems with companies, organizations and communities. Along the way, students create their experience, using the campus, city and vast natural areas of California as living laboratories. Listed below are the lower division preparation courses for the major. To be considered for this major, you must complete the following preparatory courses by the end of spring before transfer: One course in Statistics, One year of Calculus; One year of General Chemistry with Lab, One year of Biology with Lab for the major (Evolution, Cellular), and Completion of the following courses is STRONGLY RECOMMENDED : One semester of Organic Chemistry Third semester of Calculus One year of Calculus Based Physics to include (Mechanics, Electricity, and Magnetism). General Biology with Lab for the major (Molecular). All courses must be taken for a letter grade. For more information regarding this major and UCLA's transfer selection process, visit https://ioes .ucla.edu and https:// admission.ucla.edu . PLEASE NOTE: the community college courses listed below have been approved to satisfy the preparation for this major at UCLA, but they may not be exact equivalents of the UCLA courses listed.",
    "The Calculus for Life Sciences courses listed below have been approved as substitutes for UCLA's Math 3ABC series through Spring 2019. However, students may be required to complete additional math courses after transfer to satisfy this requirement. The community college statistics course included on this agreement has been approved as a substitute for Statistics 12 or 13 which means it may not transfer as an exact UCLA equivalent."
